/*---------------------------------------------------------------------------*\
  softener_brackish --- ion-exchange SOFTENING removes the scaling driver.

  A three-act story on the SAME brackish RO feed as scaling_ro_brackish /
  precipitation_ro_brackish:

    (1) raw            scalingScan of the raw water: calcite SI > 0 already at
                       the feed and climbing with recovery -- the SCALING
                       PROBLEM (a CaCO3-supersaturated concentrate).
    (2) softened       the `exchange` op equilibrates the SAME water with a
                       strong-acid cation resin (SAC_Na, Gaines-Thomas).  Ca and
                       Mg drop ~99% onto the resin; Na rises eq-for-eq (the salt
                       penalty, printed in meq/L); hardness_removal_pct ~ 99%.
    (3) softened_scaling
                       feed the SOFTENED composition (Ca/Mg gone, Na up) into a
                       scalingScan: SI_calcite is now NEGATIVE across the whole
                       recovery range -- the scaling DRIVER is gone.  Removing the
                       hardness, not chasing the supersaturation, is the cure.

  MODEL (visible in the verbosity>=3 trace): the SAME log-space Newton as
  speciate, PLUS one master (the free resin site X-), one balance (CEC capacity
  = sum of equivalents on the sites), and the exchange half-reactions
  Me(z+) + z X- = MeX (Gaines-Thomas equivalent-fraction activity for the bound
  species, Davies for the aqueous ions).  Divalent Ca2+ (logK 0.8) is
  equivalent-fraction-favoured and outcompetes Na+; watch the per-iteration
  selectivity ratio beta(CaX2)/beta(NaX)^2 climb.

  CROSS-CHECK TOOL: PHREEQC EXCHANGE (same Gaines-Thomas half-reactions).

  THE FRESH-RESIN CAVEAT (printed loudly, non-suppressible): the `exchange` op
  returns the LIMITING (fully-equilibrated) effluent -- the best a fresh /
  fully-loaded contactor does per pass.  A real fixed bed leaks rising hardness
  as the exchange front migrates to breakthrough, then must be regenerated;
  cycle length and breakthrough are TRANSIENT and not modelled here.

  Brackish water (I ~ 0.03-0.06): Davies-valid, no Pitzer needed; the honesty
  banner + the I>0.5 Davies advisory cover the boundary.

  Data: case-local constant/electrolyte/ (self-contained USGS PHREEQC snapshot,
  public domain, + the SAC_Na resin nameplate).
\*---------------------------------------------------------------------------*/

operations
(
    // -- (1) the RAW water: the scaling problem (calcite SI > 0) ----------------
    {
        name        raw;
        type        scalingScan;
        totals      { Ca 84 mg/L; Mg 27 mg/L; Na 363 mg/L; K 12 mg/L;
                      Cl 510 mg/L; SO4 250 mg/L; HCO3 183 mg/L; }
        pH          solve;
        recovery    { from 0; to 0.85; n 18; }
        output      { file scan_raw.csv; }
    }

    // -- (2) SOFTEN the same water on a SAC resin (Na form) ---------------------
    {
        name        softened;
        type        exchange;
        totals      { Ca 84 mg/L; Mg 27 mg/L; Na 363 mg/L; K 12 mg/L;
                      Cl 510 mg/L; SO4 250 mg/L; HCO3 183 mg/L; }
        pH          solve;
        exchange    { resin SAC_Na; CEC 2.0 eq/L; }   // heavily dosed: limiting effluent
        diagSpecies ( CaX2 MgX2 NaX );
        output      { file softened.csv; }
    }

    // -- (3) the SOFTENED water, scanned: SI_calcite now NEGATIVE ---------------
    //    The softened composition (Ca/Mg ~ gone, Na up eq-for-eq) read off the
    //    op (2) effluent.  Carrying it forward by hand is the honest workflow:
    //    streams carry the information, no hidden side-channel.
    {
        name        softened_scaling;
        type        scalingScan;
        // post-exchange aqueous totals (mol/kg) from op (2)'s softened effluent
        // (cations from the exchange WATER-after ledger; anions unchanged from
        // the feed -- only cations exchange):
        totals      { Ca 2.467e-7 mol/kg; Mg 2.271e-7 mol/kg; Na 2.2508e-2 mol/kg;
                      K 6.957e-7 mol/kg; Cl 1.43852e-2 mol/kg; SO4 2.60254e-3 mol/kg;
                      HCO3 2.99902e-3 mol/kg; }
        pH          solve;
        recovery    { from 0; to 0.85; n 18; }
        output      { file scan_softened.csv; }
    }
);
